SIMPLE: iniquity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Iniquity
<hw>In*iq"ui*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Iniquities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>iniquitee</ets>, F. <ets>iniquit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, L.
<ets>iniquitas</ets>, inequality, unfairness, injustice. See
<er>Iniquous</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Absence of, or deviation from, just dealing; lack of
rectitude or uprightness; gross injustice; unrighteousness; wickedness;
<as>as, the <ex>iniquity</ex> of bribery; the <ex>iniquity</ex> of an
unjust judge.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till the world from his perfection fell⟦br⟧
Into all filth and foul <qex>iniquity</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An iniquitous act or thing; a deed of injustice or
unrighteousness; a sin; a crime.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>iniquities</qex> have separated between you and your
God.</q> <rj><qau>Is. lix. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A character or personification in the old English
moralities, or moral dramas, having the name sometimes of one vice and
sometimes of another. See <er>Vice</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Acts old <qex>Iniquity</qex>, and in the fit⟦br⟧
Of miming gets the opinion of a wit.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iniquous</ent>⟦br⟧
